In a relatively modernised environment than that of mainland China, Taiwanese families are beginning to recognise that a marital breakdown is not necessarily the end of a person’s life. However, a higher proportion of men, at 90.7%, believe that a divorcee acquires a social inferiority which will prejudice them for employment and romance, as opposed to their counterpart female population of 69.6 per cent, proves that there is a stigma imposed upon divorcees by the males in Taiwan, which only serves to perpetuate this attitude among men. Unsurprisingly, women feel less let down by the subsiding of a life-long bond than men, with only 70.4 per cent considering such a situation “a failure”. 17.7 per cent of men are of the opinion that the mental turmoil that divorcees experience in the period immediately following their separation will constitute them to be a “failure”, compared to only 2 per cent of females who in a similar position. In chapter three, we will discuss the idea of an unsuitable feminine image portrayed by the media. Image problems may also confirm instances of social classes playing a prevalent role in that marriage, divorce and women spend in Taiwan, two were addressed in this chapter. From our exchange of mail and visit to Taiwan last year, there are quite a few interesting areas in older generations opinions on marriage, divorce and women.
